<worksheet xml:id="ws-complex-numbers">
  <title>Complex Numbers</title>
  <definition xml:id="lecture-notes-def-definition-of-i">
    <title>Definition of <m>i</m></title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The <term>imaginary number</term> <m>i</m> is the positive solution to the equation <me>x^2+1=0</me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    Powers of <m>i</m> are really easy to calculate, and unlike real numbers, there are only four values you have to memorize since the powers cycle through four unique values.
  </p>
  <p>
    <md>
      <mrow>i^0 \amp= 1 \amp i^4 \amp= (i^2)^2 = (-1)^2 = 1</mrow>
      <mrow>i^1 \amp= i \amp i^5 \amp= i^4 \cdot i^1 = 1 \cdot i = i</mrow>
      <mrow>i^2 \amp= -1 \amp i^6 \amp= i^4 \cdot i^2 = (1)(-1) = -1</mrow>
      <mrow>i^3 \amp= i^2 \cdot i^1 = -i \amp i^7 \amp= i^4 \cdot i^3 = -i</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>
  <p>
    The pattern continues forever like this.
    If we look at the first four exponents—<m>0,1,2,3</m>—these are the possible remainders you get when you divide an integer by <m>4</m>.
    Notice that the powers of <m>i</m> that have the same remainder after dividing the exponent by <m>4</m> will have the same value.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="lecture-notes-thm-divisibility-rule-for-4">
    <title>Divisibility Rule for 4</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        An integer is divisible by <m>4</m> if its last two digits form a number that is divisible by <m>4</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  <note xml:id="lecture-notes-note-divisibility-rule-in-terms-of-remainders">
    <title>Divisibility Rule in Terms of Remainders</title>
    <p>
      In the language above, this means that a number is divisible by <m>4</m> if you divide the last two digits by <m>4</m> and get a remainder of <m>0</m>.
    </p>
  </note>

  <lemma xml:id="lecture-notes-lem-computing-powers-of-i">
    <title>Computing Powers of <m>i</m></title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        To evaluate <m>i^n</m> for any positive integer <m>n</m>, complete the following steps.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li><p>Divide the last two digits of <m>n</m> by <m>4</m> using long division and determine the remainder. You should get <m>0</m>, <m>1</m>, <m>2</m>, or <m>3</m>.</p></li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The remainder tells you which power of <m>i</m> to use from this list.
              <md>
                <mrow>i^0 \amp= 1 \amp i^1 \amp= i \amp i^2 \amp= -1 \amp i^3 \amp= -i</mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </lemma>

  <exercise xml:id="lecture-notes-ex-compute-a-power-of-i" workspace="2in">
    <title>Compute a Power of <m>i</m></title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Compute <m>i^{487562438573735}</m>.
