  <definition xml:id="lecture-notes-def-complex-number">
    <title>Complex Number</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be any real numbers.
        A <term>complex number</term> is any number of the form <me>a+bi</me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    Do complex numbers really exist?
    It turns out that complex numbers are just another way to describe points <m>(a,b)</m> in the coordinate plane.
    For example, the point <m>(3,4)</m> can also be represented by the complex number <m>3+4i</m>.
    But there is a subtle difference.
    Instead of thinking of it as the corner of a rectangle, we think of <m>3+4i</m> as an arrow pointing from the origin to the point <m>(3,4)</m>.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="lecture-notes-fig-rectangular-and-complex-visualization">
    <caption>Two ways to visualize the point <m>(3,4)</m>. In rectangular coordinates, it is represented as a dot. As a complex number, it is represented as an arrow pointing from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(3,4)</m>.</caption>
    <image source="chapter-4-6/rectangular-and-complex.png" width="50%">
      <shortdescription>An arrow labeled 3+4i points from the origin to the point (3,4).</shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <lemma xml:id="lecture-notes-lem-how-to-add-complex-numbers">
    <title>How to Add Complex Numbers</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>a+bi</m> and <m>c+di</m> be any two complex numbers.
        Then
        <me>(a+bi)+(c+di)=(a+c)+(b+d)i</me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        In other words, just add like terms.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </lemma>

  <exercise xml:id="lecture-notes-ex-adding-two-complex-numbers" workspace="1in">
    <title>Adding Two Complex Numbers</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Perform the operation <m>(3-4i)+(-2+9i)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <lemma xml:id="lecture-notes-lem-how-to-subtract-complex-numbers">
    <title>How to Subtract Complex Numbers</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>a+bi</m> and <m>c+di</m> be any two complex numbers.
        Then
        <me>(a+bi)-(c+di)=(a-c)+(b-d)i</me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        In other words, distribute the negative and add like terms.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </lemma>

  <exercise xml:id="lecture-notes-ex-subtracting-two-complex-numbers" workspace="1in">
